Video by @danwintersphoto and @beckythale

Incandescent lava coursed from a ridge on the island of La Palma last year. Homes, shops, churches, cropland, and schools once sat in the 3.5 miles between the new volcano and the sea. Now they’re all entombed in stone, and the community is facing a landscape that's forever changed.

Photo and video by Carsten Peter

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | This adorable female desert hedgehog can be found throughout much of northern Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. To avoid the desert heat, these critters will spend most of the day sleeping, often near rocks and cliffs that help conceal them from birds of prey. Once the sun goes down, the hedgehogs will prowl for insects and other prey species. Video taken @epaa_shj. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me, @joelsartore. #hedgehog #desert #female #animal #wildlife #video #footage #spines #PhotoArk

node.text: Video by Pete McBride @pedromcbride | The brevity of time and life quickly becomes evident when filming the funeral pyres on the banks of India's Ganges River in Varanasi, a pilgrimage center for Hindus. From our documentary film "Holy (un)Holy River," which focused on the contamination of this river. For more from India, follow @pedromcbride. #India #ganges #rivers #water #life #culture #time #petemcbride

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | Raccoons, like this crab-eating raccoon at @elparquedelasleyendas in Lima, Peru, have some of the most nimble hands seen in nature. In fact, this species was actually named for its skillful paws, with “raccoon” coming from the Powhatan word “aroughcun” (when translated, this means “animal that scratches with its hands”). While most animals rely on sight, scent, or sound to hunt, these mammals depend on their sense of touch to locate food. To heighten this sense, raccoons will do something called dousing, in which they wet their paws to stimulate nerve endings. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark, follow @joelsartore. #raccoon #crabeating #mammal #animal #wildlife #video #footage #dousing #hands #paws #washing #PhotoArk

node.text: Video by @bertiegregory | Lion cubs play in Zambia’s South Luangwa National Park. These cubs belong to a pride that specializes in hunting buffalo. Considering buffalo have huge horns and a grumpy attitude, and can weigh nearly 2000 lbs (900kg), taking them on is no easy task. So while this cub play might look like fun, it’s critical training for adult life when they’ll be helping the pride bring down lunch. Filmed for my new show coming later this year to @disneyplus. #EpicAdventuresWithBertieGregory

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | Helmeted hornbills are glorious birds—and coveted in the illegal wildlife trade for their solid casques, or helmets. Softer than ivory, they can be carved into beads and statuary. As if sensing the threat, these birds fiercely protect their young: The male helps seal the female inside the cavity of a tree for months, bringing food to her and the chick through a tiny slit. When it’s time for the young to fledge, the hornbills chisel away the seal. A logger who’d heard the birds squawking inside a tree that was cut down brought them to Malaysia’s @penangbirdpark. These hornbills were lucky. Deforestation is a major threat to this species’ survival, and in most cases, birds still sealed inside a tree would die. But this man knew how rare they were and brought them to the bird park. It’s not easy to keep these birds alive when their habitat has disappeared. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me, @joelsartore. #bird #hornbill #helmeted #casque #animal #wildlife #saveourwildlife #video #PhotoArk

node.text: Video by @joelsartore | A giant desert centipede scurries across the frame during a Photo Ark shoot @melbournemuseum in Australia. This species can be found in both dry and moist habitats, usually in sheltered places such as under logs or rocks or in leaf litter. A solitary predator, the giant centipede may bite if disturbed or handled—while painful, the bite from this species is not fatal. To see more species featured in the Photo Ark follow me @joelsartore. #centipede #giant #wildlife #animal #video #australia #PhotoArk

Video by Muhammed Muheisen @mmuheisen | I believe that children are the real victims of conflict. They do not get to choose where they are born or their circumstances. Children from all over the world share the same things in common: They all seek fun, joy, and happiness. In this video, a group of Afghan refugees plays on the outskirts of Islamabad, Pakistan. 

Today is World Refugee Day, observed on June 20 each year and dedicated to raising awareness of the plight of those throughout the world who have been forced to flee their homes. For more photos and videos of the refugee crisis, follow me @mmuheisen and @mmuheisenpublic. For more on how to get involved, follow @everydayrefugees. #MuhammedMuheisen #EverydayRefugees #WorldRefugeeDay #MakingaDifference

node.text: Forests are central to solving the two biggest crises of our time, biodiversity loss and climate change. node.text: Photos by @estherhorvath | A forest of old spruces, firs, and beeches surrounds the Wilder See (Wild Lake) in Germany’s Black Forest National Park. In 1911 the forest around the lake was designated a protected area, protecting its trees and the myriad species—mushrooms, lichens, moss, snails, beetles, mammals—that make a home there. Many of these species thrive on dead wood, which in primeval forests can make up about a third of the wood total. Biologist Nicole Ottawa and photographer Oliver Meckes, the co-founders of Eye of Science, collected samples of earth from this part of the Black Forest and documented them in their lab using a scanning electron microscope. See the results—and read more about the marvelous creatures they uncovered—at the link in bio. Please follow @estherhorvath for more stories.

A new image from the James Webb Space Telescope has given scientists a stunning look at the dusty belts of debris surrounding Fomalhaut, one of the brightest stars in the night sky. Similar to the asteroid belt in our own solar system, these orbiting rings of shattered rock and ice can help reveal how planetary systems form.

node.text: Video by @andrea_frazzetta | In Africa’s Rift Valley, the Danakil Depression is a land made of salt and lava. A kind of ghost ocean, it’s what remains from an inland sea that evaporated 20,000 years ago, leaving a desert of salt. This vast plain is the homeland of the Afar people, who have adapted to survive in one of the most inhospitable places on Earth. They’ve managed to keep a strong identity despite a nomadic lifestyle. Their economy, based on extracting salt and other minerals, remains  precarious as they struggle with a hostile climate. Follow @andrea_frazzetta for more images and stories.

Photo by @jasperdoest | In his workshop in Mardin, Turkey, 28-year-old Hasan Kızıl puts the finishing touches on a custom wheelchair for a stray pup paralyzed in a car accident. 

Kızıl earned himself the nickname "life repairer" for his work in helping animals with deformities or limb loss with whatever materials he has on hand. He looks forward to witnessing an animal begin to move again. "That moment is beautiful," he says. "Once I put the prothesis on, their whole center of gravity goes to the wheels. First they are scared of walking, but then in five minutes they start running." 

Follow me @jasperdoest for more on the relationship between humankind and nature.

node.text: Photos by Charlie Hamilton James @chamiltonjames | A camera trap set on an animal trail in Wyoming's Bridger-Teton National Forest captured these "locals" over a period of several summer months. At the time I lived in nearby Jackson Hole, and I'd check the trap every couple of weeks to change the batteries and SD cards—and to see what it had captured. On one occasion, I saw that a grizzly bear had passed down the trail within a few hours of me being there. After that, I stopped servicing the camera alone and instead would take my dog and kids with me—they made so much noise that no self-respecting bear would have remained in the area.

node.text:
Photos by @erintrieb | The LaGrange and Elkhart Counties of northern Indiana are home to the third largest Amish settlement in America—about 30,000 Amish live there. Historically, the Amish shy away from technology, work predominantly in farming or carpentry, and forgo modern amenities such as electricity, cars, and telephones. I had the rare opportunity of spending a few days with several families who invited me to see and photograph their culture and traditional way of life.

Pictured here: (1) Two boys ride their horses. (2) A group of women and children eats ice cream during a charity horse ride to raise money for the community. (3) Family members feed and water the Belgian horses they raise. (4) A farmer holds his daughter on their farm.

For more stories on cultures from around the world, follow @erintrieb.
